    "## Government of India Act 1919 (Montagu–Chelmsford Reforms)",
    "### Background",
    "• Indian demand for greater representation in governance.",
    "• Montagu’s August Declaration of 1917 promised 'progressive realization of responsible government'.",
    "• Home Rule Movement (Tilak & Annie Besant) increased pressure.",
    "### Provisions",
    "• Legislative Powers: Distribution between Centre and Provinces.",
    "• Separation of Budgets: Provincial budgets separated from Central.",
    "• Dyarchy in Provinces: Subjects divided into transferred (ministers) & reserved (Governor with executive council).",
    "• Bicameralism at Centre: Imperial Legislative Council became Upper House & Lower House.",
    "• Direct Elections: Introduced for both Houses; majority members elected directly.",
    "• Indians in Viceroy’s Executive Council: Three Indians included (other than C-in-C).",
    "• Extended Communal Representation: To Sikhs, Christians, Anglo-Indians, Europeans.",
    "• High Commissioner for India: Office created in London to handle Indian affairs.",
    "• Public Service Commissions: Provision for creation; set up in 1926.",
    "• Statutory Commission: To review Act after 10 years (led to Simon Commission in 1927).",
    "• Secretary of State Salary: Paid by British exchequer instead of Indian revenues.",
    "### Significance",
    "• First experiment with dyarchy and limited responsible government.",
    "• First direct elections in India; new political awakening.",
    "• Communalism institutionalized further.",
    "• Criticized as inadequate by nationalists; INC launched Non-Cooperation Movement later.",
    "## Government of India Act 1935",
    "### Background",
    "• Post-WWI political demands and Round Table Conferences.",
    "• Simon Commission (1927) recommendations + White Paper (1933).",
    "### Provisions",
    "• Provincial Autonomy: Dyarchy abolished; responsible governments in provinces (1937–1939).",
    "• Dyarchy at Centre: Planned but never implemented.",
    "• Bicameralism in Provinces: Introduced in 6 provinces (Bengal, Bombay, Madras, Assam, U.P., Bihar).",
    "• Division of Powers: Central, Provincial & Concurrent lists; Residuary with Viceroy.",
    "• All-India Federation: Provinces + Princely States (never came into force as states refused to join).",
    "• Separate Electorates Extended: To depressed classes (SCs), women, workers.",
    "• Franchise: Extended to about 10% of population (35 million people).",
    "• Federal Court: Set up in 1937 to adjudicate Centre–Province disputes.",
    "• Reserve Bank of India: Provided for establishment (1935) to regulate currency & credit.",
    "• Public Service Commissions: Federal PSC, Provincial PSCs, Joint PSCs.",
    "• Council of India (created in 1858) abolished.",
    "### Significance",
    "• First elections across provinces in 1937; INC formed ministries in many provinces.",
    "• First attempt at federal structure in India.",
    "• Most comprehensive pre-independence constitutional reform.",
    "• Many provisions of the Indian Constitution (federal structure, PSC, RBI, federal court) borrowed from it."
